# Manual API smoke tests — Docker Control Plane API
#
# Curl requests for poking the API by hand. The service listens on 8448
# (local: `just run`; compose: `just up` maps 8448:80).
#
# Usage: copy a block into your shell. `-i` prints the status line + headers so
# you can eyeball the response code; pipe to `jq` if you have it for pretty JSON.
#
#   BASE=http://localhost:8448
#   CID=<paste a container id from POST /containers>

@BASE=http://localhost:8448
@CT_ID_CREATED={{create_ct.response.body.id}}
@DEPLOYMENT_ID=8ba2978b3b9d343ecab97428a0a1fa10e74e8aac8ce22a8b755687751dfbbf6f

### --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
### Health — pings the Docker daemon
### --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
curl {{BASE}}/health

### --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
### Live container operations (Docker is the source of truth)
### --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #

### List all containers (running + stopped)
curl {{BASE}}/containers

### Create a container (pull + create). Returns the container id — capture it.
# @name create_ct
curl -i -X POST {{BASE}}/containers \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"image": "nginx:latest", "name": "a01"}'

### Inspect one container's live status
curl {{BASE}}/containers/{{CT_ID_CREATED}}

### Start it (status is reloaded after, so it reflects the real daemon state)
curl -X POST "{{BASE}}/containers/{{CT_ID_CREATED}}/start"

### Stop it
curl -X POST "{{BASE}}/containers/{{CT_ID_CREATED}}/stop"

### Force-remove it
curl -X DELETE {{BASE}}/containers/{{CT_ID_CREATED}}

### Unknown container -> 404
curl -i "{{BASE}}/containers/deadbeef"

### Unknown image -> 404
curl -i -X POST {{BASE}}/containers \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"image": "no-such-image:nope", "name": "bad"}'

### --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
### Deployment history (SQLite-backed audit log — survives container removal)
### --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #

### All deployment records (most recently updated first)
curl {{BASE}}/deployments

### One deployment record (still present after the container is deleted)
curl {{BASE}}/deployments/{{DEPLOYMENT_ID}}

### Unknown deployment -> 404
curl {{BASE}}/deployments/unknown_deployment_id

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Async deploy via the RabbitMQ queue
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# There is no HTTP endpoint for this — the worker consumes the queue. Publish a
# message with the Justfile recipe, then watch it land in /deployments:
#
#   just publish nginx:latest queued-web
#   curl -i "{{BASE}}/deployments"
